elements.content: Antimony compounds are widely used as catalysts for the synthesis of the commercially important polymer poly(ethyleneterephthalate) by polycondensation of bis(hydroxyethyl)terephthalate. The precise nature of the antimony catalysts is, however, unknown. The present study has been conducted with a view to determining the nature of the catalytic species by structurally characterizing antimony ethylene glycolate compounds and related catecholate derivatives, namely [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n , [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n , [pySb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O, and [pyH][Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)2].

The precise nature of the antimony catalysts is, however, unknown, and the present study reports the X-ray structures of antimony ethylene glycolate compounds that are catalysts for the polycondensation reaction.

elements.content: Poly(ethylene terephthalate), PET, is the most common thermoplastic polyester and is manufactured with a variety of brand names, including Dacron, Mylar, and Terylene. PET has numerous applications, with more than 85% being processed into fibers, while a significant and growing application of PET is the manufacture of gastight bottles for carbonated beverages. PET is obtained commercially by two methods, both of which involve polycondensation of bis(hydroxyethyl)terephthalate (BHET) but differ in terms of the feedstock (Scheme ). One method employs dimethyl terephthalate and involves generation of bis(hydroxyethyl)terephthalate by transesterification with ethylene glycol at temperatures of 150−200 °C. This process is catalyzed by a variety of metal complexes (typically acetates of Ca, Mg, Zn, Cd, Pb, or Co), and the methanol released is distilled out of the reaction vessel to shift the equilibrium. A more recent method for generating BHET involves direct esterification of terephthalic acid with ethylene glycol. Regardless of the method and catalysts used to synthesize BHET, antimony-based catalysts are generally considered to be the most efficient for achieving the polycondensation reaction.
elements.clean_text:
Introduction

Poly(ethylene terephthalate), PET, is the most common thermoplastic polyester and is manufactured with a variety of brand names, including Dacron, Mylar, and Terylene. PET has numerous applications, with more than 85% being processed into fibers, while a significant and growing application of PET is the manufacture of gastight bottles for carbonated beverages. PET is obtained commercially by two methods, both of which involve polycondensation of bis(hydroxyethyl)terephthalate (BHET) but differ in terms of the feedstock (Scheme ). One method employs dimethyl terephthalate and involves generation of bis(hydroxyethyl)terephthalate by transesterification with ethylene glycol at temperatures of 150-200 °C. This process is catalyzed by a variety of metal complexes (typically acetates of Ca, Mg, Zn, Cd, Pb, or Co), and the methanol released is distilled out of the reaction vessel to shift the equilibrium. A more recent method for generating BHET involves direct esterification of terephthalic acid with ethylene glycol. Regardless of the method and catalysts used to synthesize BHET, antimony-based catalysts are generally considered to be the most efficient for achieving the polycondensation reaction.

The most common antimony compound used in these polycondensation reactions is antimony trioxide (Sb2O3). The detailed mode of action is not known, although it has been suggested that the general role of a polycondensation catalyst is to coordinate the ester carbonyl group of BHET and thereby promote nucleophilic attack by the hydroxyl group of another molecule. However, despite the efficiency of Sb2O3, drawbacks to the use of this compound include the formation of side-products (such as acetaldehyde) and catalyst decomposition depositing elemental antimony, which imparts an undesirable gray color to the polymer. As a result, more efficient polyesterification catalysts have been sought. Three such antimony compounds that exhibit polycondensation catalytic activity are antimony triacetate, Sb(OAc)3, antimony ethylene glycolate, [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n , and the hybrid complex [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n . In this report, we describe structural studies on a series of antimony ethylene glycolate and acetate complexes as part of an effort to provide insight into the nature of the species that exist in this catalytic system.

elements.content: 1. Molecular Structures of the Ethylene Glycolate Complexes [Sb 2 (OCH 2 CH 2 O) 3 ] n and [Sb(OCH 2 CH 2 O)(OAc)] n . [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n , which is typically obtained by the reaction of Sb2O3 with ethylene glycol, is believed to be the active catalyst component in the condensation polymerization of BHET to PET. However, the molecular structure of [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n is unknown, although it has been represented as the discrete dinuclear species illustrated in Figure . To determine the precise nature of the structure of [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n , crystals suitable for X-ray diffraction were obtained by crystallization from hot ethylene glycol. The molecular structure of [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n as determined by X-ray diffraction is illustrated in Figure . Interestingly, the structure of [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n does not correspond to the dinuclear species represented in Figure but, rather, is polymeric, consisting of one-dimensional chains (Figures −3). Unlike the representation in Figure , the repeat unit in each chain has two different antimony environments (Figures −3), the principal difference of which is the binding mode of the glycolate ligands. Thus, one antimony (Sb1) is coordinated in a bidentate fashion to a single nonbridging glycolate ligand and in a unidentate manner to two bridging glycolate ligands, whereas the other antimony (Sb2) is coordinated in a bidentate fashion to two bridging glycolate ligands (Figures and ). Despite the difference in glycolate coordination modes, the environment about both antimony centers is similar in terms of the Sb−O bond lengths (Table ). Specifically, both antimony centers possess three short and one long Sb−O bonds, corresponding to covalent and dative−covalent interactions, respectively (Figures and ); the short Sb−O bond lengths average 2.02 Å, while the long bonds average 2.42 Å (Table ).

The primary coordination about each antimony in the one-dimensional chain is supplemented by secondary Sb···O interactions between chains that result in the formation of a two-dimensional sheet (Figure ). Thus, Sb1 contacts O11 and O21 of an adjacent chain at a distance of 2.62 and 2.75 Å, while Sb2 contacts O11 of an adjacent chain at a distance of 2.91 Å. Thus, the Sb−O bond lengths in [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n fall into three classes:  2.0 Å (normal covalent), 2.4 Å (dative covalent, intrachain), and 2.6−2.9 Å (interchain). Further comparison, however, is not possible because of the absence of structurally characterized antimony(III) ethylene glycolate complexes in the Cambridge Structural Database.

elements.content: [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n , which may be synthesized by the reaction of Sb(OAc)3 with ethylene glycol, is also an active catalyst for polycondensation of BHET. The molecular structure of [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n , however, was unknown. Nevertheless, several possibilities for the structure [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n were proposed, some of which have antimony centers that are not coordinated to acetate (Figure ). The previous inability to determine the structure of [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n is undoubtedly a manifestation of its insolubility. To solve this problem, crystals of [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n suitable for X-ray diffraction were obtained by slow diffusion between layers of Sb(OAc)3 in THF and ethylene glycol in THF, separated by an additional layer of THF. The molecular structure of [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n , as determined by X-ray diffraction, is illustrated in Figures −7. Although the molecular structure of [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n does not correspond directly to any of the previous proposals, each of which involve three-coordinate antimony centers, it is clearly related to the top proposal of Figure , that is, Sb(η2-OCH2CH2O)(OAc). Specifically, the structure of [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n consists of a one-dimensional chain in which the oxygen atoms of the glycolate ligand of each [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] fragment bridge to the antimony centers of two adjacent fragments. The three Sb−O bond lengths within the [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] fragment are short, averaging 2.03 Å, while the bridging interaction is long (2.47 Å), as summarized in Table . The bridging interactions result in the [Sb(OCH2CH2O)] fragment forming a planar array from which the acetate ligands are oriented perpendicularly, in an alternating up/down manner (Figure ). The uncoordinated oxygen atom of each acetate ligand interacts with antimony atoms of adjacent chains, as illustrated in Figure . However, these secondary Sb···O interactions (3.46 Å) are sufficiently close to the sum of the van der Waals radii of Sb and O (3.6 Å)13 that it is not appropriate to describe [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n as a two-dimensional polymer, and that its classification as a one-dimensional chain is more accurate. Thus, the dimensionality decreases as the ethylene glycolate composition decreases.

2. Molecular Structures of the Catecholate Complexes [pySb(1,2-O 2 C 6 H 4 )] 2 O and [pyH][Sb(1,2-O 2 C 6 H 4 ) 2 ]. In addition to studying the structures of antimony ethylene glycolate complexes, we have also examined related catecholate derivatives. Not only do antimony catecholate complexes have potential applications as polycondensation catalysts but they are also of interest with respect to a search for layered antimony(III) complexes. For example, the catecholate compound [Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O has been proposed to be a layered material capable of intercalating pyridine. Of interest to this intercalation study, we have observed that the fragment [Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O is capable of chemically binding pyridine. Specifically, the pyridine adduct [pySb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O may be obtained by reaction of Sb(OAc)3 with catechol and water in pyridine (Scheme ). Of potential relevance to the intercalation study, the pyridine may be removed from [pySb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O by heating at 90 °C under vacuum.

The molecular structure of [pySb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O has been determined by X-ray diffraction, demonstrating that each antimony has a distorted trigonal bipyramid geometry, with the oxo ligand occupying an equatorial site, and the pyridine, an axial site (Figure ). The oxo bridge is distinctly bent [Sb−O−Sb = 118.2(1)°], and the Sb−O bond lengths [1.962(3) and 1.982(3) Å] are marginally shorter than those for the catecholate ligand (2.04−2.09 Å), as summarized in Table .

elements.content: An interesting aspect of the extended structure of [pySb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O, as illustrated in Figure , is that the two antimony centers supplement the primary bonding by different means. Thus, while one of the antimony centers (Sb2) supplements the bonding by interacting with an oxygen atom (3.43 Å) of an adjacent molecule, resulting in an [Sb2O2] rectangular motif (Figure ), the other antimony interacts with the benzene ring of a catecholate ligand (Figure ). The arene ring interacts symmetrically with the antimony, with an average Sb···C distance of 3.7 Å and an Sb···centroid distance of 3.4 Å. Complexes with symmetric arene−Sb interactions are not common, but examples are known for trihalide derivatives, for example, (C6Et6)SbCl3 (Sb···centroid = 2.96 Å)16a and (9,10-dihydroantharcene)SbBr3 (Sb···centroid = 3.27 Å).

elements.content: In the absence of water, Sb(OAc)3 reacts with catechol in pyridine to give [pyH][Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)2]. The molecular structure of [pyH][Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)2] has been determined by X-ray diffraction, as illustrated in Figure . The antimony coordination environment in the anion [Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)2]- may be described as distorted trigonal bipyramid with a stereochemically active lone pair occupying an equatorial site. The Sb−O bond lengths are in the range 2.01−2.19 Å (Table ), with the longest corresponding to the oxygen atom that is engaged in a hydrogen bonding interaction with the pyridinium counteranion, with an O···N distance of 2.73 Å. A similar antimony coordination geometry is observed for the related complex, [NH4][Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)2], and other derivatives. It is noteworthy that the structure of [Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)2]- is similar to that of the arsenic analogue but differs from the bismuth counterpart which exists as a dimeric species; for (pyH)[Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)2], the Sb···O distance between adjacent molecules is 3.53 Å so that it does not represent a significant interaction.

General Considerations. All manipulations were performed using combinations of glovebox, high-vacuum, and Schlenk techniques. Solvents were purified and degassed by standard procedures. Sb(OAc)3 and [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n were a gift from ATOFINA Chemicals, Inc. Ethylene glycol (Aldrich, 99.8%) and pyridine were dried over activated 4 Å molecular sieves. Catechol (Aldrich, 99%+) was dried by triturating several times with dry tetrahydrofuran, followed by drying in vacuo overnight. 1H NMR spectra were recorded on a Bruker Avance 400 DRX spectrometer. 1H chemical shifts are reported in ppm relative to SiMe4 (δ = 0) and were referenced internally with respect to the protio solvent impurity.

Sb(OAc)3 and [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n  were a gift from ATOFINA Chemicals, Inc. Ethylene glycol (Aldrich, 99.8%) and pyridine were dried over activated 4 Å molecular sieves. elements.content:
Crystallization of [Sb 2 (OCH 2 CH 2 O) 3 ] n . Crystals of [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n suitable for X-ray diffraction were obtained by slow cooling of a solution in warm ethylene glycol.

Synthesis and Crystallization of [Sb(OCH 2 CH 2 O)(OAc)] n . [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n was prepared by a literature method. A solution of Sb(OAc)3 (1.00 g, 3.35 mmol) in benzene (ca. 40 mL) was treated with a solution of ethylene glycol (0.21 g, 3.35 mmol) dissolved in benzene (ca. 20 mL), resulting in the rapid formation of a white precipitate. The mixture was stirred at room temperature overnight. The product was isolated and washed with benzene (ca. 20 mL) to give [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n (0.44 g, 55%). Crystals suitable for X-ray diffraction were obtained by sequentially layering a solution of Sb(OAc)3 (1.00 g, 3.35 mmol) in THF (ca. 40 mL), a layer of THF (ca. 20 mL), and a layer of ethylene glycol (0.21 g, 3.35 mmol) in THF (ca. 30 mL). The mixture was left to stand, undisturbed, overnight, producing crystals of [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n .

elements.content: Synthesis and Crystallization of [Hpy][Sb(1,2-O 2 C 6 H 4 ) 2 ]. A mixture of catechol (0.74 g, 6.7 mmol) and Sb(OAc)3 (1.00 g, 3.35 mmol) in pyridine (ca.. 25 mL) was stirred overnight. After this period, the volume of the yellow solution was reduced to ∼2 mL, at which point a large mass of yellow crystals formed. The mixture was filtered, and the yellow crystals of [Hpy][Sb(1,2-O2C6H4)2] were washed with pentane (3 × 15 mL) and dried in vacuo (1.29 g, 92%).

elements.content: Synthesis and Crystallization of [Sb(1,2-O 2 C 6 H 4 )] 2 O. A mixture of catechol (0.74 g, 6.7 mmol) and Sb(OAc)3 (2.00 g, 6.7 mmol) was treated with pyridine (ca. 50 mL) in a Schlenk tube. Water (60 μL, 3.34 mmol) was added to the surface of the pyridine and allowed to diffuse into the solution for several minutes before stirring was initiated. The mixture was stirred for 4 days, over which period the initially pale yellow color of the solution fades and a floculant white precipitate forms. The solid was isolated by filtration, washed with benzene (ca. 30 mL), and dried in vacuo, giving [pySb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O (0.95 g, 45%) as a white solid. Crystals suitable for X-ray diffraction were obtained by allowing the combined filtrate and benzene washing to stand at room temperature. [pySb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O is insoluble in common solvents, but its composition is confirmed by 1H NMR spectroscopic analysis of a sample degraded in methanol-d 4 by addition of DCl in D2O (2 drops of 20%) which revealed a 1:1 ratio of pyridine to catechol. Anal. Calcd for C22H18N2O5Sb2:  C, 41.7%; H, 2.9%; N, 4.4%. Found:  C, 40.6%; H, 2.7%; N, 4.3%. Crystal data, data collection, and refinement parameters are summarized in Table . The structures were solved using direct methods and standard difference map techniques and were refined by full-matrix least-squares procedures on F 2 with SHELXTL (Version 5.03).

elements.content: The molecular structures of antimony catalysts for the synthesis of PET by polycondensation of bis(hydroxyethyl)terephthalate have been determined by X-ray diffraction. Specifically, the structures of both [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n and [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n were determined to be polymeric, with the former complex forming two-dimensional sheets and the latter forming one-dimensional chains involving secondary Sb···O interactions. The dinuclear catecholate complex, [pySb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O, obtained by reaction of Sb(OAc)3 with catechol and water in pyridine, also possesses an extended structure. However, the structure differs from those of [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n and [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n by also involving Sb···arene interactions with the benzene ring of a catecholate ligand.
elements.clean_text:
Summary

The molecular structures of antimony catalysts for the synthesis of PET by polycondensation of bis(hydroxyethyl)terephthalate have been determined by X-ray diffraction. Specifically, the structures of both [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n  and [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n  were determined to be polymeric, with the former complex forming two-dimensional sheets and the latter forming one-dimensional chains involving secondary Sb⋅⋅⋅O interactions. The dinuclear catecholate complex, [pySb(1,2-O2C6H4)]2O, obtained by reaction of Sb(OAc)3 with catechol and water in pyridine, also possesses an extended structure. However, the structure differs from those of [Sb2(OCH2CH2O)3] n  and [Sb(OCH2CH2O)(OAc)] n  by also involving Sb⋅⋅⋅arene interactions with the benzene ring of a catecholate ligand.
